    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, attorneys and escrow companies typically charge a fee for their services. This fee is usually a percentage of the total sale price and is often paid by the seller, although it can sometimes be negotiated to be split between the buyer and seller. The fee compensates the attorney or escrow company for their time and the services they provide in managing the escrow process.\n\nTo ensure that the money will be released to the seller once everything is signed and done, the escrow agreement, which is part of the purchase contract, outlines the specific conditions that must be met for the funds to be disbursed. These conditions are agreed upon by both the buyer and the seller at the beginning of the transaction. Once the conditions are satisfied, the escrow agent will release the funds to the seller.\n\nAdditionally, the escrow company or attorney is a neutral third party, and their primary interest is to ensure that the transaction is completed according to the terms of the agreement. They have a professional and legal obligation to follow through with the release of funds once all conditions are met. If there are any disputes or issues, the escrow agent will typically work with both parties to resolve them before releasing the funds. If a dispute cannot be resolved, it may result in legal action, but this is",
